SIMPLE: they
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: They
<hw>They</hw> <pr>(⟦th⟧⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>pron. pl.</pos>;
<wordforms><pos>poss.</pos> <er>Theirs</er>; <pos>obj.</pos>
<er>Them</er></wordforms>. <ety>[Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧eir</ets> they,
properly nom. pl. masc. of <ets>s⟦amac⟧</ets>, <ets>s⟦umac⟧</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧at</ets>, a demonstrative pronoun, akin to the English
definite article, AS. <ets>s⟦emac⟧</ets>, <ets>se⟦oacute⟧</ets>,
<ets>⟦edh⟧aet</ets>, nom. pl. <ets>⟦edh⟧⟦amac⟧</ets>. See
<er>That</er>.]</ety> <def>The plural of <xex>he</xex>, <xex>she</xex>,
or <xex>it</xex>. <ex>They</ex> is never used adjectively, but always as
a pronoun proper, and sometimes refers to persons without an antecedent
expressed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jolif and glad <qex>they</qex> went unto <qex>here</qex> [their]
rest⟦br⟧
And casten <qex>hem</qex> [them] full early for to sail.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>They</qex> of Italy salute you.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. xiii.
24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Blessed are <qex>they</qex> which do hunger and thirst after
righteousness.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. v. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>They</ex> is used indefinitely, as our ancestors
used <xex>man</xex>, and as the French use <xex>on</xex>; as,
<ex>they</ex> say (French <xex>on dit</xex>), that is, it is said by
persons not specified.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thialdine</ent>⟦br⟧
